  "dimension": "anti-pattern-avoidance",
  "score": 3,
  "rationale": "Across the five turns, the coach avoids the priority AoA anti-patterns. Turn 2 reframes the client's self-questioning without fighting the inner critic or labeling it a limiting belief. Turn 4 introduces the 'you're also a suspect' invitation playfully rather than as accusation — sidestepping fixing-people and dont-fight-identity while gently declining to collude with the victim frame. The coach does not give partner-picking advice (resisting the fixing-people bait in turn 1), does not validate the disdain for exes, does not deploy methodology jargon (no view-as-technique or evangelizing), and the question density is low and connective rather than extractive (no wonder-as-strategy). There is no loving-to-transform push for breakthrough, no safety-as-control, and the coach holds steady through the client's prickly eye-roll in turn 5 (though we don't see the response). Positive avoidance of the baited 'help me figure out my pattern' detective frame is visible in turn 4.",
  "evidence_turns": [2, 4],
  "turn_annotations": [
    {"turn": 2, "polarity": "+", "annotation": "Asks about the quality of the self-questioning without arguing with it — avoids dont-fight-the-voice and limiting-belief-meta-trap."},
    {"turn": 4, "polarity": "+", "annotation": "Playful 'what if you were a suspect' declines the victim frame without accusation; avoids fixing-people and dont-fight-identity while gently introducing agency."}
  ],
  "expected_territory_hits": ["looking-for-whats-wrong", "i-dont-buy-your-story"],
  "expected_territory_misses": ["if-i-were-inherently-good", "what-are-you-defending"],
  "notes": "Short conversation; scoring on what's present. No anti-pattern trips observed."
}
